{"parse":{"title":"Townsite","pageid":8339163,"revid":801012589,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>A <b>townsite</b> is a legal <a href=\"/wiki/Subdivision_(land)\" title=\"Subdivision (land)\">subdivision of land</a> for the development of a <a href=\"/wiki/Town\" title=\"Town\">town</a> or <a href=\"/wiki/Community\" title=\"Community\">community</a>.  In the historical development of the <a href=\"/wiki/United_States\" title=\"United States\">United States</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Canada\" title=\"Canada\">Canada</a>, and other former <a href=\"/wiki/Kingdom_of_Great_Britain\" title=\"Kingdom of Great Britain\">British</a> <a href=\"/wiki/Colonialism\" title=\"Colonialism\">colonial</a> <a href=\"/wiki/Nation\" title=\"Nation\">nations</a>, the <a href=\"/wiki/Filing_(legal)\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Filing (legal)\">filing</a> of a townsite <a href=\"/wiki/Plat\" title=\"Plat\">plat</a> (United States) or <a href=\"/wiki/Plat\" title=\"Plat\">plan</a> (Canada) was often the first legal act in the establishment of a new town or community.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Townsites_in_British_Columbia\">Townsites in British Columbia</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Townsite&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Townsites in British Columbia\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>Numerous townsites were filed in <a href=\"/wiki/British_Columbia\" title=\"British Columbia\">British Columbia</a>, Canada, in the early 19th century. Some of those filed in what is now <a href=\"/wiki/Metro_Vancouver\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Metro Vancouver\">Metro Vancouver</a> included:\n</p>\n<ul><li><a href=\"/wiki/Gastown\" title=\"Gastown\">Granville</a> Townsite, 1870<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> (Gastown, <a href=\"/wiki/Vancouver\" title=\"Vancouver\">Vancouver</a>)</li>\n<li>Hastings Townsite, 1869 (Vancouver)</li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/North_Vancouver,_British_Columbia_(city)#History\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"North Vancouver, British Columbia (city)\">Moodyville</a> Townsite, 1865 (City of North Vancouver)</li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/New_Westminster\" title=\"New Westminster\">New Westminster</a> Townsite, 1860 (original capital of Colony of British Columbia, now New Westminster)</li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/North_Vancouver,_British_Columbia_(city)\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"North Vancouver, British Columbia (city)\">North Vancouver</a> Townsite, 1907<sup id=\"cite_ref-multiple_2-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-multiple-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> (City of North Vancouver)</li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Port_Mann\" title=\"Port Mann\">Port Mann</a> Townsite, 1911<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> (Surrey)</li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Steveston\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Steveston\">Steveston</a> Townsite, 1889 (<a href=\"/wiki/Richmond,_British_Columbia\" title=\"Richmond, British Columbia\">Richmond</a>)</li></ul>\n<p>Although most of these townsites were incorporated into newly created cities and municipalities of Metro Vancouver, official survey plans still continue to designate <a href=\"/wiki/Land_lot\" title=\"Land lot\">lots</a> as being part of these townsites. For example, a 2008 strata plan in Vancouver's Gastown is indicated as being in the Granville Townsite.<sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>Townsite planning was either done by government authorities or by private developers. In the case of North Vancouver townsite in 1907 most of the land was owned by the North Vancouver Land and Improvement Company.\nBy owning large amount of land they were able to plan on a grand scale.<sup id=\"cite_ref-multiple_2-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-multiple-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> New Westminster was surveyed by the Royal Engineers under government direction.\n</p><p>As existing towns grow, they develop <a href=\"/wiki/Official_Community_Plan\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Official Community Plan\">Official Community Plans</a> (OCPs) that expand upon the already existing townsites. However, periodically new communities are still created. In 1975, the <a href=\"/wiki/Whistler,_British_Columbia\" title=\"Whistler, British Columbia\">Whistler</a> townsite was created and eventually incorporated as a municipality. The new municipality was given 53 acres (210,000&#160;m<sup>2</sup>) of <a href=\"/wiki/Crown_land\" title=\"Crown land\">Crown land</a> to develop the townsite.<sup id=\"cite_ref-5\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Townsite&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Vancouver, A Visual History, Bruce MacDonald, 1992, page 18</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-multiple-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-multiple_2-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-multiple_2-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">North Vancouver Official Community Plan 2002, Chapter 2, Historical overview</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-3\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">New townsite of Port Mann, Ottawa Citizen, Feb 2, 1911, page 2, Canadian Press dispatch</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-4\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-4\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external free\" href=\"https://www.scribd.com/doc/12560230/36-Water-Street-The-Terminus-Strata-Plan\">https://www.scribd.com/doc/12560230/36-Water-Street-The-Terminus-Strata-Plan</a></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-5\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-5\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.whistlerhorizons.com/whistlerhistory.shtml\">Chronological milestones in the development of Whistler Village</a></span>\n</li>\n</ol></div></div>\n<p><br />\n</p>\n<table class=\"metadata plainlinks stub\" role=\"presentation\" style=\"background:transparent\"><tbody><tr><td><a href=\"/wiki/File:Armillary_sphere.png\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"Stub icon\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/82/Armillary_sphere.png/30px-Armillary_sphere.png\" width=\"30\" height=\"39\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/82/Armillary_sphere.png/45px-Armillary_sphere.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/82/Armillary_sphere.png/60px-Armillary_sphere.png 2x\" data-file-width=\"810\" data-file-height=\"1059\" /></a></td><td><i>This article about <a href=\"/wiki/Geography\" title=\"Geography\">geography terminology</a> is a <a href=\"/wiki/Wikipedia:Stub\" title=\"Wikipedia:Stub\">stub</a>. You can help Wikipedia by <a class=\"external text\" href=\"//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Townsite&amp;action=edit\">expanding it</a>.</i><div class=\"plainlinks hlist navbar mini\" style=\"position: absolute; right: 15px; display: none;\"><ul><li class=\"nv-view\"><a href=\"/wiki/Template:Geo-term-stub\" title=\"Template:Geo-term-stub\"><abbr title=\"View this template\">v</abbr></a></li><li class=\"nv-talk\"><a href=\"/wiki/Template_talk:Geo-term-stub\" title=\"Template talk:Geo